 <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/2575364.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dashanvaliant>DashanValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/20/03 1:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A wee bit of advice</span><hr size=1> <br>
Two things leap to mind.<br>
<br>
A)  Turn logging on.  In the EQ config file, I believe changing it from :<br>
LOG = FALSE<br>
<br>
to <br>
<br>
LOG = TRUE<br>
<br>
will do this.  Clean it out every few weeks if nothing untoward happens.  It logs everything, yes, but it will only end up being a few hundred meg at most.  (Yeah, that *is* a lot of text; but it's better than missing something important).  This ensures if something needs to be reported, it can be.  In extreme cases, I imagine e-mailing Sony with the relevant text would be equivalent to a petition.  I assume they can verify anything sent.<br>
<br>
B)  Ignore now has 100 slots.  While I don't believe it will get rid of emotes in the vicinity; it will eliminate the direct communication that seems to be the major problem.  <br>
<br>
Far far better to have 100 people on ignore than to be run off by harassment.  Get your friends to copy your ignore list if you are worried about someone trying to stalk you by proxy (and, of course, character assassination).  <br>
<br>
And of course, you also get to revel in the fact that those on ignore will shrivel up and die without someone to harass...<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fauxknight>Fauxknight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/20/03 1:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=39.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Stalking on EQ</span><hr size=1> Most of these type problems are indeed two sided, and I suggest making sure the one who is 'being stalked' also knows what she should and should not be doing to prevent causing any more commotion. I'm not trying to judge her here, just suggestion you make sure you have taken an objective view of things. <br>
<br>
It looks like Imasu has tried to control the situation on his guilds side, there isn't much more he can do. Telling an entire guild they shouldn't communicate with someone or else be /guildremoved is a bit extreme. If thats the case then I would believe they are taking the problem very seriously. It is hard to imagine the kind of chaos that would have to have been caused in order for my guild to issue that kind of order.<br>
<br>
Ignore is way to solve the problem if civil negotiations don't work. Maybe not the best solution, but it will somehwat alleviate the problems in game (obviously not on message boards or anywhere else out of game though). <br>
